Intuition
when looking at this problem first thought was adding strings from front using 2 pointers but then i realized if i will add values from front i will loose some important values , so new strategy was i knew array is already sorted so i started from behind as there are empty spaces at back of the array so i compared biggest of both the arrays and i knew one of them is going to be at the end , so i initalized a 3rd pointer at the end of nums1 so i was storing the biggest value at the end of nums1 and traversing whole list using j pointer and when j pointer gets out of the loop the array will be sorted

Approach
initalize :
i = m - 1
j = n - 1
k = m + n -1
loop condition till j >= 0:
when element of i are bigger than element of j and i is inside the list : update elements and move pointer of i
else : update elmenets and move j pointer
k pointer moves after every iteration

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Space complexity:
O(1)
Code
class Solution:
    def merge(self, nums1: List[int], m: int, nums2: List[int], n: int) -> None:
        """
        Do not return anything, modify nums1 in-place instead.
        """
        i = m - 1
        j = n - 1
        k = m + n - 1

        while j >= 0:
            if i >=0 and nums1[i] > nums2[j]:
                nums1[k] = nums1[i]
                i -= 1
            else:
                nums1[k] = nums2[j]
                j -= 1
            k -= 1
